Looking at the different variables listed in your summary, including the distribution of income you just computed, which of these variables are factor / categorical variables? Of these, how many are binary (only two possible outcomes)? Which variable is numeric / continuous? How can you tell?

We know age and education are numeric since the vary from person to person (they are continuous). Employed, violent.exp.ISAF and violent.exp.taliban are binary because there are only 2 options, 0 and 1. Income is (should be) a factor variable since it has different categories of income

Descriptive statistics: binary variables

Lets take a look at descriptive statistics for two binary variables: people who experienced violence from the ISAF (violent.exp.ISAF) and people who experienced violence from the Taliban (violent.exp.taliban). The most useful descriptive statistics for binary variables like this are the proportion (use select to identify the variables of interest, then obtain the proportion using the summary command), and the frequency distribution (use the count command). Keep in mind that NA means missing (the respondent did not answer this survey question). Recall that for binary variables coded with 0s and 1s, the mean is equivalent to the proportion.

afghan %>% 
  select(violent.exp.ISAF, violent.exp.taliban) %>%
  summary()
##  violent.exp.ISAF violent.exp.taliban
##  Min.   :0.0000   Min.   :0.0000     
##  1st Qu.:0.0000   1st Qu.:0.0000     
##  Median :0.0000   Median :0.0000     
##  Mean   :0.3749   Mean   :0.3289     
##  3rd Qu.:1.0000   3rd Qu.:1.0000     
##  Max.   :1.0000   Max.   :1.0000     
##  NA's   :25       NA's   :54
count(afghan, violent.exp.ISAF)
## # A tibble: 3  2
##   violent.exp.ISAF     n
##              <dbl> <int>
## 1                0  1706
## 2                1  1023
## 3               NA    25
count(afghan,violent.exp.taliban)
## # A tibble: 3  2
##   violent.exp.taliban     n
##                 <dbl> <int>
## 1                   0  1812
## 2                   1   888
## 3                  NA    54

We see that about 35.5% of people experienced violence by the ISAF and 32.89% experienced violence by the taliban.

In regards to violence by the ISAF, 1706 did not experience violence (0) while 1023 did (1). 25 people did not answer (NA). For the taliban, 1812 people did not, 888 people did and 54 did not answer.

Lets visualize the distribution of these two variables separately using a bar plot for each. Treat missing values (NA) as a category of its own. Start with the ggplot function and specify the dataset (afghan). Next, specify the first aesthetic (aes) with variable of interest for the x-axis, (for example, as.factor(violent.exp.ISAF)), keeping in mind that as.factor tells R to treat this variable as a categorical or factor variable. Next, specify the type of plot, geom_bar, with a second aes that indicates what will be on the y-axis (..prop.., group = 1 for proportion rather than count). Finally, you can add labels for the categories of the variable (scale_x_discrete(labels = c()), x and y axes (xlab() and ylab(), and overall plot ggtitle()).

#Bar plot for ISAF violence
afghan %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.factor(violent.exp.ISAF))) + # changes ISAF violence to a factor variable and will use it as x axis
  geom_bar(aes(y=..prop.., group=1)) + # specifies a proportion graph where all groups add to 1, geom_bar is used for bar plot
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("No Harm", "Harm", "No Response")) + # adds labels to x axis categories
  xlab("Response Category") + # x axis title
  ylab("Proportion of Respondants") + # y axis title
  ggtitle("Civilian Victimization by the ISAF") # plot title

#Bar plot for Taliban violence
afghan %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.factor(violent.exp.taliban))) + # changes Taliban violence to a factor variable and will use it as x axis
  geom_bar(aes(y=..prop.., group=1)) + # specifies a proportion graph where all groups add to 1, geom_bar is used for bar plot
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("No Harm", "Harm", "No Response")) + # adds labels to x axis categories
  xlab("Response Category") + # x axis title
  ylab("Proportion of Respondants") + # y axis title
  ggtitle("Civilian Victimization by the Taliban") # plot title 

# see lab 3 vid for other way to do it if needed

Now, lets combine the two bar plots so we can compare values more easily. First, reshape the dataset using pivot_longer to get a single column specifying whether the violence is caused by the ISAF or the Taliban. Then, use ggplot and the commands fill, group, and position to combine the barplots on the same graph.

#First, reshape the data
afghan_reshape= afghan %>%
  pivot_longer(violent.exp.ISAF:violent.exp.taliban, names_to = "harming_group", values_to="harm")
# names_to harming_group assigns ISAF and Taliban to be distinct bars in the plot
#values_to sends the values of each (no harm, harm, no response) to a new variable "harm" for later use

#Next, bar plot with both harm indicators together
afghan_reshape %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.factor(harm))) + # take harm variable from before and make it a factor variable 
  geom_bar(aes(y=..prop..,
               fill=harming_group, # different color per group
               group=harming_group), # assign values to respective group 
           position="dodge") + # don't stack bars, put them side to side 
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("No Harm", "Harm", "No Response")) + # adds labels to x axis categories
  scale_fill_discrete(name="harming group", labels=c("ISAF", "Taliban")) +
  xlab("Response Category") + # x axis title
  ylab("Proportion of Respondants") + # y axis title
  ggtitle("Civilian Victimization by the ISAF and Taliban") # plot title

##Descriptive statistics: Continuous variables

In general, recall that we like to get a sense of central tendency (mean, median) and dispersion (IQR, standard deviation/variance) about numeric or continuous variables. Lets start by obtaining the mean, median, and IQR for the variable age using the select and summary. (Hint: calculate the IQR yourself by subtracting the 3rd quartile from the 1st quartile).

afghan %>%
  select(age) %>%
  summary()
##       age       
##  Min.   :15.00  
##  1st Qu.:22.00  
##  Median :30.00  
##  Mean   :32.39  
##  3rd Qu.:40.00  
##  Max.   :80.00

We see that the mean is 32.29, and the median is 30. The summary table gives us the 1st quartile = 22 and the 3rd quartile = 40, thus IQR = 18

Now, lets obtain the IQR (to check your work above), standard deviation, and variance for age using the summarize() command and filling in the parentheses with the desired descriptives (IQR, sd, var) for the variable age.

afghan %>%
  summarise(IQR=IQR(age), sd=sd(age), var=var(age))
## # A tibble: 1  3
##     IQR    sd   var
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1    18  12.3  151.

IQR is 18, sd = 12.29 and var = 151.03

Now, lets visualize the distribution of age using a histogram using the ggplot function. Specify the data and the first aesthetic (aes) with variable of interest for the x-axis, age. Next, specify the type of plot, geom_histogram, with a second aes that indicates what will be on the y-axis (density), the binwidth (how wide each histogram bin will be), and the boundary (the bin position). Finally, you can make further specifications such as the spacing of the tick-marks on the x-axis (scale_x_continuous), and labels for the whole plot and your x and y axes (labs()).

afghan %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=age)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),
                 binwidth=5) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(20,80,10)) + # sequence of 20-80 by 10
  labs(title="Distribution of Respondent Age", y="Density", x="Age")

Finally, lets look at the distribution of age using a boxplot. use ggplot with the data afghan, aes() specifying age on the Y-axis, followed by the command geom_boxplot. Specify labels for x, y, and title using labs().

afghan %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=age)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(y="Age", title="Distribution of Age")
